# my-chezmoi

Reference for working in Derek's chezmoi-managed dotfiles. Source tree: `~/.local/share/chezmoi`.
One source tree serves multi-OS / multi-machine configs via templating + conditionals.

## Apply workflow (operational — every time)

- After editing ANY managed dotfile, run `chezmoi apply <target-path>` immediately — live files are
  stale until applied, so testing is impossible otherwise.
- Pass **target paths** (`~/.config/nvim/init.lua`), NOT source paths (`dot_config/exact_nvim/...`) —
  source paths return a "not managed" error.
- Preview: `chezmoi diff`. Subset re-run: `chezmoi apply --include scripts`.
- From a **git worktree**, a bare `chezmoi apply` reads the *main* source tree and silently ignores
  your worktree edits. Test worktree edits with `mise run worktree-apply <target>` (wraps
  `chezmoi apply --source "$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel)" <target>`).
- A config file created outside the source tree must be added to chezmoi management before finishing.

## File-name prefixes (decoded into $HOME)

| Prefix | Meaning |
| --- | --- |
| `dot_` | becomes `.` in home |
| `exact_` | dir syncs deletions (removes untracked) |
| `private_` | restrictive perms; content via 1Password |
| `run_once_before_` / `run_once_after_` | runs once ever, before/after files |
| `run_onchange_*` | runs when its content (or `.tmpl` inputs) change |
| `run_before_` / `run_after_` | runs every apply |
| `.tmpl` | Go template, rendered at apply |

Platform suffixes filtered by `.chezmoiignore.tmpl`: `.darwin.*`, `.linux.*`, `.windows.*`,
`.unix-like.*` (cross-Unix only), `.shared.*`. Prefer OS-specific files over in-script `uname` branching.

## Script stages (`.chezmoiscripts/<NN>/`)

`00` sudoers · `10` core/system deps · `20` dev deps (mise, opam) · `30` shell registration ·
`40` app deps (xpip/uv) · `50` symlink sync · `65` log rotation · `70` editor plugins ·
`90` specialized (terminfo, Riot P4/LoL) · `99` git-commit backup snapshots. Every script logs
start/end to stderr (`echo >&2 "INFO: Starting $0"` / `Ending`).

## Machine detection (`.chezmoi.toml.tmpl` `[data]`, snake_case)

`is_my_machine` (dmf) · `is_riot_machine` (dfrank / RIOTGAMES) · `is_work_machine` ·
OS: `is_darwin` `is_linux` `is_windows` `is_unix_like` `is_bsd`. Credentials flow through 1Password
(`onepasswordRead()`) at render time; `OP_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_TOKEN` must be exported for `chezmoi init`
(fail-loud), and mise injects it afterwards from `~/.config/mise/conf.d/secrets.toml` (0600) — run
chezmoi via `mise x -- chezmoi ...`.

## Templating

- Shared fragments in `.chezmoitemplates/`, included via `{{ "{{" }} includeTemplate "..." . {{ "}}" }}`. Canonical
  example: `.chezmoitemplates/agents/AGENTS.md.tmpl` rendered into each AI tool config.
- Machine-specific data in `.chezmoidata/` (MCP servers, projects, packages, models).
- Access optional map fields with `index $pkg "key"`, NOT `$pkg.key` (dot-notation panics on missing
  keys; `index` returns nil/falsy).
- `.tmpl` highlighting is auto-handled by the nvim config; add a `# vim: ft=gotmpl.<lang>` modeline
  only when the filename lies about the body (e.g. a `.json.tmpl` whose body is Python) AND the
  comment won't leak into rendered output (`modify_*` scripts are safe; direct-render configs aren't).

## Naming: snake_case for identifiers you own

All chezmoi-source identifiers use `snake_case`: `[data]` keys, `.chezmoidata/*.yaml` keys templates
read, and inline locals (`{{ "{{" }} $my_github_token := ... {{ "}}" }}`). Never camelCase.

**Exception — external-contract output keys stay verbatim.** A key mandated by another tool's config
format and emitted into rendered output belongs to that tool's namespace. Snake the SOURCE identifier;
map it back to the required key in the OUTPUT. Litmus: is the string a key in a file chezmoi renders
*for another program to read*? If yes, match that program's spelling in output and only snake the
source-side variable. Known external-output keys: `mcpServers` (MCP client config; source key is
`mcp_servers`), Ollama Modelfile `num_ctx`/`num_predict`/`temperature`, pi-mcp-adapter
`clientName`/`bearerToken`/`httpUrl`.

## Packages (`.chezmoidata/packages.yaml`)

Package lists live here, never hardcoded in scripts (except bootstrap-critical deps in `.bootstrap.*`
scripts). Bootstrap rule: any tool a `modify_*` script needs is a bootstrap dep — install it in all
three `.bootstrap.*` scripts and mark `bootstrap: true` (modify_* runs in Phase 2, before any
run_after_ chezmoiscript in Phase 3). Sync scripts back up before+after to
`.backups/<tool>.<user>.<host>` and git-commit each snapshot.

## Backups

`.backups/` is git-tracked, auto-committed by stage-99 scripts. Snapshots named
`<tool>.<user>@<hostname>.log`, captured before and after install/upgrade for an audit trail.

## Validation

- `mise x -- pre-commit run --all-files` (shellcheck, shfmt, ruff, stylua, prettier, template
  validators). Single hook: `mise x -- pre-commit run <hook-id> --all-files`. The `mise x --` prefix is
  required (pre-commit is mise-managed).
- `mise run test` — regression harness, organized by subsystem under `.tests/<domain>/`.
- pre-commit hooks are the contract: fix the source file when a hook fails; never add `# noqa`,
  extend `exclude:`, or skip a hook without approval.

## Commits

Conventional commits describing the repo's desired-state change (not the downstream machine effect):
`chore(...)` for package-inventory changes, `fix(...)` for broken repo behavior, `feat(...)` only for a
new user-facing managed capability. One logical change per commit; scope = subsystem (`homebrew`,
`git`, `zsh`).
